You still fail to consider the specific usage case that I described and the OP reiterated: <em>not looking for folders with a specific known tag</em>, instead simply wanting to compare and contrast folders based on their tags.  Windows Search is useless in that context; the only way it can be accomplished is with a standard Explorer view configured with a column to display comments FOR FOLDERS.<br /><br />Shall I give you a specific usage example?  It's not relevant to me any more, but it demonstrates the issue:<br /><br />I used to collect erotic image sets from USENET.  They came from all different sorts of sources, and I wanted to document those sources.  Initially I tried to keep that information in the folder name for each set, but path names have a finite length.  I wanted to use comment metadata, but that only worked for files, not folders.  I wanted to be able to view that list of set folders and see and be able to sort upon their sources as found in comment metadata.<br /><br />That simply wasn't possible then.  It still isn't.<br />13<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=11237">VulcanTourist</a> — Fri Aug 21, 2015 12:20 pm</p><hr />
